text: hi everyone anthony fantano here the
internet's busiest music nerd and it's
time for a review of the new self-titled
factory floor album factory floor is a
musical trio hailing from the uk this is
their second full-length album
depending on whether or not what they
previously released actually qualifies
as an album either way i've really been
looking forward to this album merely
because i loved one of the singles that
dropped previous to this thing i love
this band's
sonic aesthetic essentially factory
floor makes old-school dance music
really rigid rudimentary electronic
dance music with influences coming from
old school house some acid house too and
it's like they strip a lot of these
sounds back to be as simple and as
minimal as possible reappropriating a
lot of old-school drum machine sounds
and synth textures in the process and
undeniably these guys pulled together
some really hard edged grooves
do they have momentum down to a science
on this lp and a lot of their other
tracks too these are beats that you just
have to kind of move to however i would
not say the factory floor songs are all
that melodic or traditionally structured
like a song with a verse chorus so on
and so forth but what does that really
matter there are plenty of great dance
songs that aren't however it's like
factory floor really wants to bring this
point home like this is not poppy dance
music don't you understand we're trying
to keep this thing as noisy and as weird
as we possibly can almost to the point
where it feels like there's a really
strong industrial music vibe coming off
the music that factory floor makes or a
post punk vibe and neither are that
surprising considering one of the
members of this trio collaborated with
two members of throbbing gristle last
year on a strange little industrial
music and noise album called transverse
got it right here check it out it might
lift your skirt on this new lp factory
floor works to make these very
accessible dance grooves weird by
slathering them with very monotone drab
moaning deadpan vocals vocals that are
so intentionally drab they kinda kill
the fun mood that the dance beats bring
this was a key feature of factory floors
last release as well and doing this on
their tracks can kind of be a little bit
of a double-edged sword there are
moments where factory floor with these
very odd vocals and these hard-edged
dance beats come through with a piece of
dance music that is authentically weird
and kind of refreshing because of that
weirdness however there are spots on
this album as well where i'm not really
sure what to do should i dance or should
i just stand here stone-faced and be
kind of weirded out as far as highlights
off of this lp go there is the song fall
back a track that i heard earlier this
year that i mentioned in the beginning
of this video that i absolutely love i
love the unpredictable synth notes on
this thing the really crisp crispy drums
as well as the kind of pulsating bass
line and nick void's disconnected vocals
feel oddly sexy this song to me is just
a weird combination of being entrancing
and hypnotic but also kind of wild and
edgy as well as emotionally numbing and
off-putting there are other songs on
here too that i feel like hit that
perfect balance tracks like how you say
or work out which is a track that is
well deserving of its title and has this
synth riff that really reminds me of
early daft punk now even though there
are moments on this lp like how you say
where it feels like nick voigt is trying
to be a little more lyrical with her
vocals it is the fact that she is always
singing with the deadest of deadpans
that kind of makes this album feel
slightly one dimensional i guess the
vocal style does make this album get a
little old a little fast i mean yeah it
is kind of something that factory floor
specializes in and it's something that i
could signify as being a factory floor
thing i would know a factory floor song
if i heard it because of these vocals
but i wouldn't necessarily say that nick
void singing
makes the songs enjoyable plus on top of
it many of the tracks on this album are
are very similar in concept and i guess
you could say that a lot of the sounds
this album puts forward won't be too
unfamiliar to you as well if you are
into many a dfa records release so
unfortunately even though i really dug
the song fall back and a few other songs
on here overall this album didn't end up
feeling as refreshing to me or as
radical to me as i had hoped i feel like
many of these tracks standing alone
would work really well in a dj set for a
kind of off-kilter dance party but as
far as a listening experience to almost
a full hour of music on this thing while
i liked many of the tracks on here i did
kind of feel like i was stuck in dance
music limbo like i was just in one place
for way longer than i actually wanted to
be overall i gotta say i feel a decent
six on this lp tran position but if
you've given this factory floor album a
listen what did you think of it did you
love it hate it why what do you think i
should review next and
that's
it anthony fantano only the strong
subscribe all mistakes are intentional
factory floor self-titled
forever
